div.p:
An autograph title page by Webern, whose base layer was written in red ink, refers to a selection of nine George songs (fol. 8r in 
            H
          ):

In fact, one of the extant sources of “Dies ist ein Lied” M 133 (
            C
          ) was found in the archives of the singer Marya Freund, who had sung the Wood Dove at the first performance of Schoenberg’s Gurre-Lieder on 23 February 1913. She was also due to sing Gustav Mahler’s Kindertotenlieder at what later became known as the “Skandalkonzert” on 31 March of that same year (whose programme included the world premiere of Webern’s Six Pieces for Large Orchestra “Op. 4” [M 152–157]), though the tumult that occurred on that evening meant that the Mahler songs were never performed. According to a note in her archives, the autograph came into her possession in “circa 1914”. However, she never sang the song in the context that had been envisaged because the concert programme was initially shortened, and then the very idea of the “evening of compositions” was dropped altogether. We do not know whether Freund actually sang this song – or any George songs by Webern – on any other occasion.
